{"author":{"id":"75732e82453cc4795a3b5d7bef7a9ce916b428e5bbe06161843f7392657be5c1"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1444980182,"nonce":"1HirvC13Css7IiqEN4ALmpRH5Tc=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDE0ODYzNTgzNA==","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/332#issuecomment-148635834"},"message":"\u003e  and probably document it properly\n\nI think this is the biggest issue for metadata, and this is why it prevents (at least me) from using it. I want to take a look into it and see if I can get it working at the featureCounts side.","files":null},{"type":3,"timestamp":1444997171,"nonce":"uKHHSVFeOlpZqpP8+OIyW2w4G5s=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDE0ODY5OTgzNQ==","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/332#issuecomment-148699835"},"message":"I figured out how to do this.\n\nTo change a metadata value (e.g. named 'has_header_line') in a history item, the metadata name must be reserved and defined in the datatype. E.g. for tabular files only the following metadata elements are available and can be changed via a tool xml:\n\n```\nMetadataElement( name=\"comment_lines\", default=0, desc=\"Number of comment lines\", readonly=False, optional=True, no_value=0 )\nMetadataElement( name=\"data_lines\", default=0, desc=\"Number of data lines\", readonly=True, visible=False, optional=True, no_value=0 )\nMetadataElement( name=\"columns\", default=0, desc=\"Number of columns\", readonly=True, visible=False, no_value=0 )\nMetadataElement( name=\"column_types\", default=[], desc=\"Column types\", param=metadata.ColumnTypesParameter, readonly=True, visible=False, no_value=[] )\nMetadataElement( name=\"column_names\", default=[], desc=\"Column names\", readonly=True, visible=False, optional=True, no_value=[] )\nMetadataElement( name=\"delimiter\", default='\\t', desc=\"Data delimiter\", readonly=True, visible=False, optional=True, no_value=[] )\n```\n\nhttps://github.com/galaxyproject/galaxy/blob/dev/lib/galaxy/datatypes/tabular.py#L34\n\nBecause from these metadata variables you can not deduce whether there is a header line, you would need to add a new definition for that, probably something like:\n\n```\nMetadataElement( name=\"has_header_line\", default=False, desc=\"Is the first data line a column header?\", readonly=False, visible=True, optional=True, no_value=False )\n```\n\nOr maybe it's handier to create it as 'header_line', which represent the exact line where the header can be expected (but this should be equal to metadata.comment_lines + 1). Doing so it could solve an issue I never actually reported. For input params of the type data_column the comment lines are not being skipped:\n\n```\n#header1\n#header2\n#header3\nc1  c2  c3\na   2   4\nb   1   4\nc   4   3\n```\n\n```\n\u003cparam type=\"data_column\" data_ref=\"tabular_file\" numerical=\"True\" multiple=\"true\" use_header_names=\"true\" /\u003e\n```\n\nPicks the first line to determine the columns on, also when the input file has the comments are enabled.:\n![screenshot from 2015-10-16 13 57 50](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/2264697/10541076/699519ba-740e-11e5-8578-36899a1c6725.png)\n\nBy picking the 'metadata.header_line' this could be solved, although comment_lines+1 would be fine too.\n\n---\n\nTo set the metadata you could:\n- Set it in the tool xml that generates the file\n- Let the Tabular.py parse this but this is not flawless.\n\nAt the tool xml part we should do it this way:\n\n```\n\u003cdata format=\"tabular\" name=\"output\" label=\"${tool.name} on ...\"\u003e\n    \u003cactions\u003e\n        \u003caction name=\"has_header_line\" type=\"metadata\" default=\"1\" /\u003e\n    \u003c/actions\u003e\n\u003c/data\u003e\n```\n\nWould you like to see this change to Tabular.py or would you prefer another solution?\n\nEdit: In case someone wants to play this and wants to obtain all metadata of a history item (including hidden metadata), you can use this tool:\nhttps://toolshed.g2.bx.psu.edu/view/yhoogstrate/show_metadata/","files":null}]}